reviewText: Season 2 was just as good as the first, the ONLY knock is I wish it continued and didn't end so quickly. These are some FUNNY Ladies and I miss them a lot! I promise you'll laugh until you cry, give them a chance you won't be sorry.

Title: Pulling: Season 2

reviewText: The word "brilliant" is an often times overused word in British pop culture but Pulling Season 2 is simply Brilliant. Brilliant because it's one of those sitcoms you can watch again and again and not get sick and tired of it. You see the punchline but you're still laughing. Sharon Horgan did a brilliant job in Season 2, bringing back characters who made a cameo appearance in season one and giving them more substantial roles in the series. Richard, Oleg, and Ian are back, as is Donna's frenemy Tanya.Louise's ingenious business idea had me bawling over in laughter. Let me put it this way: you will never think of popsicle the same way ever again! Karen gets even worse as she hooks up with her old flame Billy. But I must say episode 2 of Season 2 was Donna at her most egotistical and self-centered best: her old friend Catherine, who lives in the US but is back in England on a visit. She has been invited to a dinner party hosted by Donna at her flat.The scene at the cafe highlights what a great actress Sharon Horgan can be without saying anything. Catherine, who had been wearing the same exact cardigan when she met Donna, was ordering coffee. Donna slowly gazes down noticing her best friend's cardigan. When Catherine turns around and looks at her, Donna just flashes a sweet, innocent smile. Before the dinner party was about to begin, Donna tidies her flat and, to show off what a sophisticated thinker she is to her old friend, takes the Al Gore documentary An Inconvenient Truth, a film she rented but hadn't seen, and prominently displays it on her book case. Just smart comedic acting by Horgan without speaking any words.
Title: Pulling: Season 2

reviewText: This is easily the funniest show I've seen in many years, and brilliantly pulled off by writers and actors. It's got physical comedy, verbal comedy, and situational comedy, all handled with equal aplomb and timing that's a marvel to watch. The skill on display here, from everyone, is all the more impressive for seeming so effortless. It might take you a little time to catch the show's rhythm and sensibility, but once you do, you'll be hooked. I know I am.
Title: Pulling: Season 2

reviewText: Both season one and two are absolutely hilarious. The sad part is that there are only six episodes per season and you are certainly going to be  wishing there were more! The entire cast is great, the story lines are entertaining and you just keep wishing it wouldn't end.
